# Neural Networks

## Lesson Highlight: Neural Networks Activity

<img src="https://images.code.org/1d9eec2b4cd7ddb50ccb82d71d2223ec-96bdfbaafb6aedb4c412eb366a21876d-Slide22.PNG" alt="system prompt with role, goal, tone, and restriction" width="350px" style="float:right; margin: 20px 20px 20px 20px;">

#### During **Lesson 6: Neural Networks**, students help a computer design meals for an elementary school cafeteria.

#### Students represent food choices with a network. On the left side, we have our inputs - in this case, avocados, ice cream, raisins, and peanuts. On the right side, we have our output states: accept or reject.

#### Students then add in a **hidden layer** to their neural networks to represent different relationships and decisions such as food combinations such as avocado and ice cream.

#### The final component of the neural network is **weights**. When the network combines the weights at the end, it can look at the total weight and use that to make a final decision as to whether or not to accept or reject a set of inputs. For example, we can add lower weights to the ‚Äújust avocados‚Äù and ‚Äújust ice-cream‚Äù connections, and a higher weight to the ‚Äúboth‚Äù connection.


